ed validator while maintaining the original order, mapping the bad index accordingly. To implement this, I could allocate temporary arrays for sorting, copy inputs, and set indices while sorting all three using the same heap sort comparator.\n**Evaluating sorting options**\n\nI’m considering whether to reuse the existing sort for two arrays instead of implementing a new sift-down method for triples, which might complicate things. An alternative is to call `GGUFValidateTensorRangesSorted` on copies. If there's an error, I could refer to the sorted index by matching the offset and nbytes, but duplicates could complicate matters.\n\nHowever, since the requirement mentions feeding sorted ranges for performance reasons, I might need to sort copies and use the unsorted original index for error mapping. It's essential to check for null pointers too, given the complexity of this approach.\n**Implementing tensor byte span resolution**\n\nI'm working on implementing `GGUFTensorInfoResolveByteSpans` and need to ensure that pointers are not null. It’s essential to validate tensor byte sizes and check if there are any overlaps within the tensor ranges. Given that sorting might complicate matters, I’ll handle the sorted validation directly on copies of the tensor data. \n\nTo avoid overhead, I could work with the passed arrays directly instead of allocating new ones. This means I need to document any changes in order that might occur. I’ll also need to add error codes for allocation failures and ensure robust testing to cover various scenarios, including overlap detection and type propagation issues. Finally, I should check on required documentation and associated files to complete my implementation needs."}}
